  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_913538742" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/913538742" />
    <a title="Isaac Cooper" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25791416-isaac-cooper"><img alt="Isaac Cooper" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1393146442p2/25791416.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/913538742?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Isaac Cooper" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Isaac Cooper" href="/user/show/25791416-isaac-cooper">Isaac Cooper</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/25791416-isaac-cooper?shelf=abandoned">abandoned</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer913538742" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2198432790486960276">I can’t tell you how much, dear reader, I loathe abandoning a book. I don’t do it lightly. It’s not something that I do willy-nilly. It’s not a pleasant experience, abandoning a book. It’s kind of like a break-up. Maybe there was something once in the relationship that really made it work, but you know in your heart you have to break up. Just like I know in my heart I have to stop reading a book, for whatever reason. <br/><br/>Hell, sometimes I abandon books that aren’t terrible, like Blood Meridian or … </span>
  <span id="freeText2198432790486960276" style="display:none">I can’t tell you how much, dear reader, I loathe abandoning a book. I don’t do it lightly. It’s not something that I do willy-nilly. It’s not a pleasant experience, abandoning a book. It’s kind of like a break-up. Maybe there was something once in the relationship that really made it work, but you know in your heart you have to break up. Just like I know in my heart I have to stop reading a book, for whatever reason. <br /><br />Hell, sometimes I abandon books that aren’t terrible, like Blood Meridian or … or this one, Temple of the Golden Pavilion. Just because I abandon doesn’t mean it’s utter tripe. You know how you can tell if a book is utter tripe? If I give it one star. That rating to me is the worst of the worst, the unforgivable and completely irredeemable.<br /><br />So, what I’m saying is that this book wasn’t utterly terrible, is that it?<br /><br />Yeah, that’s right. I enjoy reading foreign books when I get the chance, they’re an interesting change of pace, sure the translation might lose a bit of its original spark, but it’s interesting all the same. This book starts off with an immediately sympathetic character, one who has a stutter and so feels like an outcast at school and wants more than anything for the WWII air raids to flatten Kyoto and Japan along with it. <br /><br />The problem is, and my god did I give it a chance to correct itself (abandoned a little more than half-way through) was that this mother*cker rambles like a … well, like a mother*ucker. It’s just insistent on rambling and often times feels like it’s got not a lot to say in terms of plot or an underlying message. We follow our stuttering-protagonist as a late-adolescent and on to a Buddhist Zen University and his aspirations to one day take over the Golden Temple and so forth, and his so called evil intentions that he wants to release to the world, but it’s just too aimless to work.<br /> <br />This is a truly fragmented book in many ways. It’s hard for me to give it such a low rating when I really do like some of the writing, I think Yukio Mishima was a great writer, he really knew how to write well, but for the life of me I can’t understand why this book is so very aimless. I hear that he originally wrote novels solely for the money, which might give some explanation. The Golden Temple itself really claims the spotlight too much, also. The protagonist is obsessed with it, and finds some connection with his own ugliness and the temple’s beauty, but there has to be more than that. <br /><br />I know in the end, spoilers, I guess, he burns down the temple, but you get to halfway through the book and he’s still admiring it, he’s still going on about the beauty of it and his inherent ugliness and how much he wishes to be evil and so on and so on. It’s interesting to begin with, I was curious for only so long before that curiosity turned in to a simple want for something else to happen. The problem, I think, is that there’s not really a character arc in the book. Okay, so maybe in the end when he burns down the temple? But that’s not a character arc, that’s just a character burning down a temple. <br /><br />My point is there doesn’t feel like any progression from the stuttering beginning of our main character, to what I suppose is meant to be the contradictory act towards the one thing he once admired. Without that arc, there is really little to keep a reader invested. This is not helped by the fact the story is told in the past tense by the main character, as if all of the events have already happened and he is reciting them from a point in the far future. <br /><br />Should you read it? <br /><br />No, I wouldn’t recommend it. There are far better books out there for you, dear reader. Even though I didn’t like it that much, I’d easily recommend Blood Meridian – my last reviewed book – over The Temple of the Golden Pavilion. <br /><br />There’s just too much rambling, too much empty writing to justify the fairly long length of the book. Sure, I said a similar thing about the somewhat repetitiveness of Blood Meridian, but at least in that there is something actively happening, albeit not as quick as I would have wanted.<br /> <br />The Temple of the Golden Pavilion is another book, like Blood Meridian, that really just could have used a big old-fashioned edit. Plain and simple. Remember, it’s always good for a book to be too short than too long. Because with one that’s too long, it’s easy for it to overstay its welcome, to have the reader become fed up with it. One that’s too short, however, leaves you wanting more, keeps you spry. <br /><br />Okay, now I’m rambling and that’s all personal preference anyway. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2198432790486960276" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


