    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2694151131" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2694151131" />
    <a title="Tsung" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung"><img alt="Tsung" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298808605p2/4992851.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2694151131?book_show_action=true">Feb 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tsung" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tsung" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung">Tsung</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2694151131" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10777245249654001748">In 1950, the 600 year old Kinkakuji was burned down by a novice monk. Mishima creates a fictional account of the person and events leading up to its destruction. The success of this novel depends on how successful Mishima is in convincing the reader of the young acolyte’s personality, thoughts and motivations.<br/><br/>The Golden Pavilion in Kyoto is beautiful, but not captivating. It may be that it is a reconstruction or it may be the thousands of tourists that rob it of its Zenness. Mizoguchi had high e</span>
  <span id="freeText10777245249654001748" style="display:none">In 1950, the 600 year old Kinkakuji was burned down by a novice monk. Mishima creates a fictional account of the person and events leading up to its destruction. The success of this novel depends on how successful Mishima is in convincing the reader of the young acolyte’s personality, thoughts and motivations.<br /><br />The Golden Pavilion in Kyoto is beautiful, but not captivating. It may be that it is a reconstruction or it may be the thousands of tourists that rob it of its Zenness. Mizoguchi had high expectations of its beauty based on his father’s praises. He was sorely disappointed when he finally saw it and regarded it as ugly. Instead he developed his own mental image of the golden pavilion, an image so perfect that he became obsessed with it.<br /><br />Mizoguchi did not have such a good childhood, with a sickly father, an immoral mother and a stutter, no wonder he was isolated, lonely and alienated. He was a sad, confused dude. So his story was one of conflicts, contrasts and contradictions. He was constantly antagonistic towards the Superior, Father Dosen, although much of it stemmed from his own delusions of persecution. His friends Tsurukawa and Kashiwagi were complete opposites, like an angel and a devil, counseling or misguiding Mizoguchi respectively. Tsurukawa was candid, the voice of reason and Mizoguchi’s conscience. On the other hand, Kashiwagi was devious, manipulative and a bad influence.<br /><br />The story was not solely about the burning of the pavilion. Some of Mishima’s own ruminations were evident within the story. There were a few philosophical discussions about the nature and perception of beauty, mainly through Kashiwagi’s speeches. There was also a misogynistic tone. Each of the women were either presented in a negative light or badly mistreated.<br /><br />So was Mishima successful in presenting Mizoguchi’s story? Yes. I am convinced that Mizoguchi was a nutter. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10777245249654001748" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


